Heat Map

cormat <- round(cor(logstudypop, use = "pairwise.complete.obs", method = c("pearson")),2)
melted_cormat <- melt(cormat) %>% rename(Correlation = value)
ggplot(melted_cormat, aes(Var1, Var2, fill = Correlation)) +
 geom_tile(color = "white") +
 scale_fill_gradient2(low = "blue", high = "red", mid = "white", 
   midpoint = 0, limit = c(-1,1), space = "Lab", 
    name = "Pearson\nCorrelation") +
  theme_minimal() + # minimal theme
 theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 1, 
    size = 12, hjust = 1),
    axis.text.y = element_text(vjust = 1, 
    size = 12, hjust = 1),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size = 15),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 15)) +
 coord_fixed() + labs(x = "", y = "", title = "Correlation Heat Map of Pollutants")

Exploratory Factor Analysis

Perform an eigenvalue analysis to get an estimate (or range) for the number of underlying dimensions. Recommend fitting as least one more and one less factor than suggested by the eigenvalue analysis.

One way to determine the number of factors or components in a data matrix or a correlation matrix is to examine the scree plot of the successive eigenvalues. Sharp breaks in the plot suggest the appropriate number of components or factors to extract. Parallel analyis is an alternative technique that compares the scree of factors of the observed data with that of a random data matrix of the same size as the original.

fa.parallel(logstudypop)

## Parallel analysis suggests that the number of factors =  4  and the number of components =  2

Orthogonal Models

Orthogonal rotation is used if it is desirable to identify factors that are as independent from one another as possible.

fa_3 <- fa(logstudypop, 
                 nfactors = 3, n.obs = 1003,
                 rotate = "varimax", #varimax is an orthogonal rotation
                 scores = "regression")
## The estimated weights for the factor scores are probably incorrect.  Try a different factor extraction method.
print(fa_3, digits = 2, sort = TRUE)

Oblique Models

Oblique rotation (i.e.correlated factors) are commonly used since we often hypothesize our latent variables of interest to be correlated with one another.

fa_3_p <- fa(logstudypop, 
                 nfactors = 3, n.obs = 1003,
                 rotate = "promax",
                 scores = "regression")
## The estimated weights for the factor scores are probably incorrect.  Try a different factor extraction method.
print(fa_3_p, digits = 2, sort = TRUE)
